<p><strong>Brush Mouse (<em>Peromyscus boylei</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Cricetidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Peromyscus boylei</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Brush Mouse<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The Brush Mouse has a length of 3⅗-4⅕ inches, a tail length of 3⅗-4⅖ inches, and a weight of 22-36 grams. Its color ranges from grayish brown to fairly dark brown washed with tawny on the sides. Its tail is well haired and is as long as its head to body length, often times longer. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=striped%20skunk&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This mouse can be found in chaparral areas of arid to semiarid regions and in rocky areas. It is a good climber, and feeds on pine nuts, acorns, seeds, and berries. It nests under rocks, in crevices, and under debris. It bears 2-6 young more than 4 times a year.</p>
